For the past 6 months, the resolution criteria was to divide the September 15 price by the May 19 price. I had missed the (now-fixed) typo and then when I realized it this morning, I thought long and hard about the resolution and recalculated and recalculated the price comparisons, to find Cardano had already met the criteria. So I made a drastic update to Cardano but leaving room for the chance it had been a typo. Lo and behold, it was, so I reverted back to XRP (Ripple). Noisy judgement because of a typo lol, but it's a good thing I accounted for this. Could be better, but we live and we learn - both as forecasters and as question administrators.
Too late for others to catch Ripple. RIP SOL.

XRP is looking to be far and apart from the rest of the crowd here, given that Solana is all but done and Bitcoin is down almost 70% YOY; Ethereum doesn't look like it will have a break out either, and Cardano is tied up in the same mess as Solana is with the FTX fallout.The trick here is we know that the leverage that crypto tokens claim in their reserves is not enough to cover, but lack of regulations and strategic accounting and financing arrangements delay the time of impact for this fallout--Mt Gox was a warning, Celsius should have been a wake-up call, and FTX will bring a lot of crypto token pricing down to reality, which is where SBF now finds himself.

Big adjustment on initial forecast due to a lack of catalyst breaking correlation of those crypto pairs. SOL close to 0% chance due to FTX association. BTC adjust down due to no apparent catalyst + recent underperformance relative to other cryptos.

It turns out having a huge crash (80% down from peak 1 year prior) in the year proceeding the measurement period is a great way to ensure you have a decent period. Buy low, sell high (or in this case, only a little bit lower).

Currently every cryptocurrency has severely dropped in price; however, bitcoin and ethereum are still leading the pack. Nevertheless, both "assets" have significantly decreased in value and as a whole cryptocurrency has severely lost any form of worth.
Not much time left for other cryptos to catch up to XRP. But Ether and BTC are most stable in these unstable times. SOL is rekt with FTX.

Despite the downward trend during the recent 7 days, XRP price as of now is still higher than the price as of May 19th 2022.

For Ripple to be displaced at this point we'd need to see one of the three coins that is down 33% pop by 40% and Ripple not have any correlated follow, or we'd need Ripple to drop by 35% and at least one of the others hold steady. Variability is high in crypto, but beta still seems highly coorelated, so an alpha move of 30% in 40 days seems very unlikely without some major event.

Ripple is a long way in front - question becomes how can it lose from here. There are big legal risks (SEC vs. Ripple). Both parties have filled "summary judgements" which essentially says "the other party has no chance of winning this case." I read reports that the summary judgements could be ruled on Oct 18, 2022. Ripple would tank if the judgement is in the SEC's favour.

I think they will all perform terribly, so to single out one as a "best performer" is like trying to guess which penny stock will pop next--probably the one we see being pumped the most in comment sections.Bitcoin is in a period of capitulation, and prices are consolidating towards the $17k range, and so we should see a "red candlestick" pop up soon to bring markets back to reality; we are still facing rising inflation and disruption of the global supply chain, and so markets are still in for a wakeup call regarding earnings--Michael Burry (of "the Big Short" fame) recently alluded to it taking "...over a decade to get pack everyone into the theater, they aren't getting out overnight", which I find is the case here with crypto markets as most of the $70b inflows over the Father's Day weekend more than likely stemmed from "piece-coining" of retail investors thinking they are buying on the dip or the "whales" which are basically manipulating market pricing and/or are buying more crypto as their "crypto-token" backed loans are now undercollateralized--these are dead cat bounces, I feel, with no reversal in sight.
